<p>Solar installation costs in Illinois have decreased significantly over the past decade, with current pricing averaging \$2.25-2.85 per watt before incentives. Equipment costs represent 60-70% of total installation expenses, including high-efficiency panels, inverters, racking systems, and electrical components. Installation labor costs vary by region, with Chicago-area installations typically 10-15% higher than downstate pricing due to labor rates and permitting complexities. These costs include design, permitting, installation, inspection, and utility interconnection.</p>

<h2>HVAC Systems in Illinois</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Illinois experiences a continental climate characterized by hot, humid summers and cold winters, creating substantial heating and cooling demands throughout the year. Summer temperatures frequently reach 85-95¬∞F with high humidity levels, while winter temperatures commonly drop to 10-25¬∞F with occasional periods below zero. This climate pattern requires HVAC systems capable of efficient operation across temperature ranges exceeding 100¬∞F differential, making equipment selection and sizing critical for both comfort and energy efficiency.</p>

<p>The state's heating season typically extends from October through April, requiring approximately 5,500-6,500 heating degree days annually in northern regions and 4,500-5,500 in southern areas. Cooling season runs from May through September, with cooling degree days ranging from 800-1,200 annually depending on location. This balanced heating and cooling load makes heat pump systems particularly attractive, as they can provide both heating and cooling efficiently while reducing overall energy consumption compared to separate heating and cooling systems.</p>

<p>Illinois's moderate humidity levels during winter months help reduce heating system strain, but summer humidity often reaches 60-80%, increasing cooling loads and making dehumidification important for comfort and indoor air quality. Modern HVAC systems with variable-speed components can better handle these humidity conditions while maintaining consistent temperatures. The state's relatively stable weather patterns, without extreme temperature swings common in mountain regions, allow for predictable HVAC system performance and energy planning.</p>

