<p>HVAC system costs in Illinois vary significantly based on system type, home size, and installation complexity. High-efficiency systems command premium pricing but offer substantial long-term savings through reduced energy consumption. Installation costs include equipment, labor, ductwork modifications when necessary, electrical connections, and permits. Chicago-area installations typically cost 15-20% more than rural locations due to higher labor costs and more complex permitting requirements.</p>

<p>Energy savings calculations are based on replacing 10-15 year old systems with modern high-efficiency equipment. Actual savings depend on home size, insulation quality, usage patterns, and utility rates. ComEd and Ameren Illinois both offer rebates for qualifying high-efficiency equipment, which can reduce upfront costs by \$500-2,000 depending on system type and efficiency ratings. These utility incentives are factored into the payback period calculations.</p>

<h2>Illinois Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Illinois offers some of the most attractive solar incentives in the Midwest through the Illinois Shines program, which provides Solar Renewable Energy Certificates (SRECs) for solar installations. Residential systems receive upfront incentive payments ranging from \$0.40-0.70 per watt depending on system size and installation type, with additional payments for installations on affordable housing or in environmental justice communities. The program guarantees these rates for approved projects, providing financial certainty for solar investments.</p>

<p>The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) remains the largest incentive available, providing a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the full installation cost including equipment, labor, and permitting fees. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, the federal credit provides \$6,000 in tax savings, which can be carried forward if it exceeds annual tax liability.</p>

<p>ComEd offers several programs supporting both solar and HVAC efficiency. The Smart Ideas Energy Efficiency Program provides rebates up to \$1,400 for high-efficiency air conditioning systems, \$1,200 for heat pumps, and \$500-1,000 for furnaces meeting efficiency requirements. Ameren Illinois provides similar rebates through their ActOnEnergy program. Both utilities offer additional incentives for smart thermostats, duct sealing, and insulation improvements that complement HVAC upgrades.</p>

<p>Property tax exemptions for solar installations ensure that increased home values from solar systems don't result in higher property taxes. Illinois also offers net metering, allowing solar customers to receive retail rate credits for excess electricity sent to the grid. Some municipalities provide additional incentives, such as expedited permitting or fee waivers for renewable energy installations. These combined incentives can reduce total system costs by 50-60% for solar installations and 15-25% for HVAC systems.</p>

